        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested Sensitivity: The objective is to determine the H13CN and HN13C distributions out to 25 K or 4" in the envelope of IRAS 2A. The sensitivity request is based on expected flux of the H13CN emission 4" offset from the protostellar center from existing SMA observations by Jorgensen et al. (2005). At 4" the expected line intensity is at least 5 mJy (assuming the same steep fall-off observed at 1-2" scale continues out to 4"). To detect lines we thus request a 1 mJy rms over the 4km/s width of the lines - the line width is also taken from Jorgensen et al. (2005).

Imaging Requirements: To image the spatial distribution H13CN, HC15N, and HN13C over the critical temperatures 100-25 K (corresponding to angular radii of 0.5-4" in the IRAS 2Aprotostellar envelope), we need a spatial resolution of 1". Both HCN and HNC are expected to be present throughout the envelope, at scales up to 20". To recover the extended emission, ACA and TP observations are required.

Correlator Setup: Band 6 allows us to image the 13C isotopologues of HNC and HCN and the 15N isotopologue of HCN in one setting, which is unique among the ALMA bands. Based on previous observations with the SMA (Jorgensen et al., 2005), the H13CN emission is expected to be optically thin. Should the H13CN be optically thick, HC15N will be used instead to eliminate any optical depth issues. All lines are imaged with ~0.3 km/s frequency resolution. The line widths are 4.2 km/s and with the requested resolution we are able to obtain ~10 resolution elements, enabling a detailed kinematic analysis. The additional windows are placed to image methanol 5-4 ladder and methyl formate. Observations of these molecules would provide additional information on the presence of complex organic molecules in this source and as such, further enhance the accuracy of current astrochemical models.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
