    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Molecules are often the best and sometimes the only probes of key aspects (e.g temperature, density, radiation) of dense interstellar environments. Isomer pairs are of special interest because variations in isomer ratios can often be connected to a single environmental parameter. HNC and HCN are such an isomer pair, with a key characteristic that both molecules are readily detected in many galactic and extragalactic sources. Based on observations and theory, their ratio is expected to mainly depend on the local temperature and may serve as a thermometer between 20 and 100 K. Attempts to calibrate this temperature probe observationally have been difficult however because of a lack of access to well-characterized, simple sources with well-understood temperature profiles. We propose to exploit ALMA's combined sensitivity and high spatial resolution to map the H13CN and HN13C 3-2 emission in the envelope of the low-mass protostar NGC1333 IRAS2a at scales corresponding to 20-100 K. We will then use the temperature structure of this source to calibrate the temperature dependence of the chemistry, developing an HNC/HCN thermometer that can be applied in galactic and extragalactic sources.</prp:abstract>
